        <body>
            <pb n="1R"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>St Thomas</placeName>
                <date>June 22<hi rend="sup">nd</hi> 1843</date>
            </p>
            <p>
                <addressee>Revd Isc. Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">
                <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">Dear Sir,</p>
            <p rend="indent(12)">I am disappointed in not being able to re„<lb/> „mit you the amount
                of the subscribtion list for the Occident.<lb/> by this opportunity, the fault is
                not mine, I told the Subscri„<lb/> „bers that they might pay on receipt of the 2nd
                Number, antici„<lb/> „parting that no retard would be experienced in the receipt of
                them<lb/> but to my astonishment <persName>Mr Wolff</persName> has received his
                    <date>May</date> Number,<lb/> and I have received none, the Subscribers are
                blaming me, but<lb/> I cannot help it, Try &amp; send them regularly by way of
                    <placeName>New York</placeName><lb/> as there are numerous opportunities from
                that City for this<lb/> place, I have collected from 5 Subscribers only, but on
                receipt<lb/> of the <date>May</date> Number, I will collect from the rest, &amp;
                remit you<lb/> forthwith. Permit me to make a few observations<lb/> which may tend
                to make the Occident more generally appre„<lb/> „ciated here. Every one reads the
                Archives Israelites &amp; the Voice<lb/> of Jacob, consequently they find the
                Occident not as interesting<lb/> as you could make it by extracts from the German
                Periodicals,<lb/> this I have promise will take place.</p>
            <p rend="indent(7)"><persName>Mr Carillon</persName> is again in the Office of
                Minister<lb/> here, and has adopted numerous innovations and alterations in<lb/> our
                religious forms &amp; observances. I am decidedly averse to<lb/> such steps, however
                much a reform might be required. I deem<lb/> it precipitate in a Congregation like
                this, or in any one Congre„</p>
            <pb n="1V"/>
            <p>„gation to change any established order. and therefore I have<lb/> withheld all
                participation in their actions.—Let us await the<lb/> result of a general conclave
                of Enlightened &amp; religious men. &amp;<lb/> then adopt what they may determine
                upon. Perhaps I may<lb/> be wrong, if so please set me right.</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">I would send you some subject on this place<lb/> but I fear the
                truth would be disagreeable to your reader here<lb/> and I prefer silence rather
                than injure you in any way.—</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">I hope soon to hear from you, and pray<lb/> that the Almighty may
                enable you to persevere &amp; succeed in<lb/> all your undertakings—</p>
            <p rend="indent(5)">I am Dear sir</p>
            <p rend="indent(5)">Yours truly</p>
            <p rend="indent(6)">
                <persName role="author">M B Simmons</persName>
            </p>
            <p>PS. Do not laugh at me, when I relate my last night's dream.—<lb/> I thought what I
                had long wished for had taken place, that is a per„<lb/> „sonal acquaintance with
                your good self. I fancied your arrival<lb/> &amp; visit to my house, that you were
                at my table &amp; read the <add>המוציא</add>
                <add>“Hamotzi” JE transcription</add> after<lb/> the meal a number of friends
                visited me, &amp; found your conversa„<lb/> „tion so agreeable &amp; instructive,
                that of one accord they declared you<lb/> could not be other than the <persName>Revd
                    I. L</persName> of <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>, while enjoying<lb/>
                their discovery. I was awakened by a <hi rend="underline">shock of Earthquake</hi>
                in reality.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Adieu—Yours</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">
                <persName role="author">MBS</persName>
            </p>
            <p rend="The following is written in pencil, bottom left corner.">Number “20-452”</p>
        </body>
